                     <interp inst="def1-1410-18390408" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">MARY ROWLEY</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18390408-1410-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18390408-1410-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18390408-1410-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp>for stealing, on the <rs id="t18390408-cd-242" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18390408-1410-offence-1 t18390408-cd-242"></join>12th of April</rs>, 1 quartern of flour, value 9<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. the goods of <persName id="t18390408-name-1441" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1441" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1441" type="surname" value="BELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1441" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18390408-1410-offence-1 t18390408-name-1441"></join>John Bell</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390408-name-1442" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1442" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1442" type="surname" value="BELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1442" type="given" value="MARY ANN"></interp>MARY ANN BELL</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of John Bell, a corn-chandler. On the 12th of April, about half-past six o'clock, the prisoner came into the shop for a pint of split-peas and some oats—while I was gone round for them, I missed a quartern of flour—I told her she bad got my property in her apron—she said she had nothing of mine—I took hold of her wrist, and took the flour out of her lap—she resisted, and burst the bag open—this is it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. LORD</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did she offer to pay for the flour? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—she said nothing whatever about it—it was on the counter—she had her apron up before her, and I suspected her.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390408-name-1443" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1443" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1443" type="surname" value="STANNARD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1443" type="given" value="REBECCA"></interp>REBECCA STANNARD</persName>
                  </hi>. I was in the parlour, and saw the prisoner come</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183904080202"></xptr>
               <p>in and ask for a pint of split-peas and a pint of oatmeal—I saw her take the flour off the counter and put it into her apron.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Was the parlour-door open? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—Mrs. Bell accused her of it—I went to her assistance, and stopped her—I heard no<lb></lb>thing about her paying for it.</p>
               <p>(The prisoner received a good character.)</p>
               <p>
